if we will construct classes by composition (passing dependencies by constructor parameters) we will have few pros

1. low coupling 

Now class CmpClientImpl is highly coupled with HttpClient. 

To proper work of HttpClient we must pass CloseableHttpClient instance as method argument (postRequest method).
Next in this method we automatically closing this resource. This could generate some errors.

What will happen when some other developer will execute below sequence?
client = createCloseableHttpClient()
HttpClient.postRequest(pkiMessage, csrMeta.caUrl(), caName, client);
and then execute
HttpClient.postRequest(pkiMessage, csrMeta.caUrl(), caName, client);

.... it will receive an error,because closableHttpClient was closed by postRequest method. 
From HttpClient.postRequest we should not have any impact on closableHttpClient created outside method.

2. user of api will exactly know what kind of objects are required to proper work 

Now we are hiding that in class is direct request over http to remote resource

3. testing is easier
For example if we will have:

class  CmpClientImpl {
  private final HttpClient httpClient;

  public CmpClientImpl(HttpClient httpClient){
    this.httpClient = httpClient;
  }
}

then in test we can use Mockito
   httpClient = mock(HttpClient.class);
   when(httpClient.postRequest(...).then(...)
   new CmpClientImpl(httpClient).createCertificate(...)

after such modification  method
  public CloseableHttpClient createCloseableHttpClient() {
    return HttpClients.createDefault();
}

could be moved to HttpClient class.

